<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - technology]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/technology <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/technology" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - technology - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 17 日星期一 23:54:56 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Restricting Chip Sales to China Could Backfire on U.S., Industry Group Says]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> SIA 警告称，潜在的限制可能会限制美国半导体公司的国内扩张<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060362"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E8DCC2B0-F066-41EA-9053-96EC3A35B05E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Frestricting-chip-sales-to-china-could-backfire-on-u-s-industry-group-says-dbb7b8df&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">芯片制造商英伟达跻身市值 1 万亿美元的公司专属俱乐部。 《华尔街日报》的 Asa Fitch 详细分析了 Nvidia 是如何实现这一目标的，以及人工智能为何推动该公司快速增长。插图：赵安妮<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060362"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/asa-fitch" itemprop="url" rel="author">阿萨·菲奇</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 6:32（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/restricting-chip-sales-to-china-could-backfire-on-u-s-industry-group-says-dbb7b8df"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>美国芯片行业贸易组织周一表示，拜登政府对向中国销售先进半导体的潜在限制可能会破坏政府对国内芯片制造的巨额新投资。</p><p>拜登政府正在考虑<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-considers-new-curbs-on-ai-chip-exports-to-china-56b17feb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对向中国出售芯片实施一系列新限制</a>，旨在破坏北京利用人工智能进行黑客攻击和武器开发的行为。与此同时，去年《 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chips-act-is-bounty-for-semiconductor-companieswith-many-strings-attached-6e72fd67?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">芯片法案》</a>通过后，政府将拨款 390 亿美元用于新建美国芯片制造工厂。</p><p>华盛顿特区的行业机构半导体行业协会在一份声明中表示：“允许该行业继续进入中国市场这一全球最大的商品半导体商业市场，对于避免破坏这一努力的积极影响非常重要。”书面声明。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818385?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">拜登总统去年参观了密歇根州的一家电脑芯片工厂。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：帕特里克·塞曼斯基/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国芯片公司长期以来一直认为，政府应该仔细权衡出口限制的影响，因为在中国的销售支持了在美国的投资，并有助于资助维持其技术优势的研究。</p><p>在中美之间以半导体和电动汽车行业为中心的紧张关系加剧后<span class="company-name-type">，</span>包括人工智能芯片领导者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVDA" class="">英伟达</a>在内的芯片公司一直在游说政府不要实施更严格的出口管制。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nvidia-warns-of-lost-opportunities-if-u-s-bans-ai-chip-exports-to-china-293fa911?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">英伟达首席财务官警告称</a>，如果禁止销售人工智能芯片，“美国工业将永远失去在中国的机会”。</p><p> SIA 表示，这些限制过于宽泛、含糊，有时甚至是单方面的，“有可能削弱美国半导体行业的竞争力，扰乱供应链，造成巨大的市场不确定性，并促使中国采取持续升级的报复行动。”它呼吁拜登政府在实施更多限制之前与业界协商。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>去年10月，美国对芯片和芯片制造设备<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-restricts-semiconductor-exports-in-bid-to-slow-chinas-military-advance-11665155702?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">实施了一些迄今为止最严格的限制</a>，要求芯片公司向美国商务部寻求许可才能向中国客户销售一些最先进的产品。</p><p>这些措施旨在阻止美国技术提升中国军事实力。</p><p>白宫国家安全委员会发言人表示：“我们的行动经过精心设计，重点关注具有国家安全影响的技术，旨在确保美国及其盟国的技术不会被用来破坏我们的国家安全。”</p><p>该发言人补充说，自去年《芯片法案》通过以来，“私营公司已宣布未来十年在美国半导体生产、供应链和研发领域投资近 1400 亿美元。”</p><p>在美国采取行动之后，中国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-bans-micron-as-supplier-to-big-chinese-firms-citing-national-security-5f326b90?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">禁止中国大型企业</a>从美国计算机内存公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MU" class="">美光科技</a>购买产品<span class="company-name-type">，</span>并于最近对<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-restricts-exports-of-two-metals-used-in-high-performance-chips-a649402b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">手机通信芯片所用金属</a>的出口实施了限制。</p><p>拜登政府<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-considers-new-curbs-on-ai-chip-exports-to-china-56b17feb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">目前正在考虑采取进一步的限制措施</a>，以限制英伟达为中国市场开发的人工智能芯片。它还正在考虑切断中国通过<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-looks-to-restrict-chinas-access-to-cloud-computing-to-protect-advanced-technology-f771613?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">云计算公司</a>获取人工智能芯片的渠道。拜登总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-grapples-with-potential-threats-from-chinese-ai-7d1f2e70?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">预计将在即将发布的行政命令中限制美国对中国先进芯片制造等技术的投资</a>。</p><p>这一行业的推动正值拜登政府试图寻找与北京的新外交机会之际。财政司司长</p>珍妮特·耶伦<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yellen-trip-aids-fragile-effort-by-u-s-china-to-keep-talking-9b78ea55?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">本月在美国官员的一系列访问中前往北京</a>，但进展迹象有限。<p></p><p>去年《芯片法案》通过后，众多芯片公司正计划在美国开展大型芯片制造项目。其中包括<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/INTC" class="">英特尔</a><span class="company-name-type">、</span>美光、<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SSNHZ" class="company-name">三星</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSM" class="">台积电，它们共同投入数百亿美元建设</a>新<span class="company-name-type">工厂</span>，政策制定者希望这些工厂将有助于扭转该行业近几十年来向亚洲转移的趋势。</p><p>写信给 Asa Fitch： <a href="mailto:asa.fitch@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">asa.fitch@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:32:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/restricting-chip-sales-to-china-could-backfire-on-us-industry-group-says-dbb7b8df</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/restricting-chip-sales-to-china-could-backfire-on-us-industry-group-says-dbb7b8df<author><![CDATA[Asa Fitch]]></author><category>人工智能技术</category><category>半导体</category><category>木制家具</category><category>消费品</category><category>家具</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>集成电路</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>美光科技</category><category>亩</category><category>英特尔</category><category>国际贸易中心</category><category>英伟达</category><category>NVDA</category><category>三星电子</category><category>005930.SE</category><category> KR:005930</category><category>台积电</category><category>2330.台湾</category><category>台湾：2330</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>半导体</category><category>木制家具</category><category>消费品</category><category>家具</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>集成电路</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ford Cuts Price of F-150 Lightning Electric Truck by Up to $10,000]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>竞争对手特斯拉开始生产 Cyber​​truck 后采取了这一举措<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059809"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="504" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818253?width=700&amp;height=504" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">福特正在降低价格，以扩大生产规模并降低成本。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ryan Garza/今日美国网络/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059809"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nora-eckert" itemprop="url" rel="author">诺拉·埃克特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 5:02（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-cuts-price-of-ev-f-150-lightning-truck-by-up-to-17-2cc21c6a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/F" class="company-name">福特</a>周一将其电动 F-150 Lightning 皮卡车的价格下调了近 17%，这是最新迹象，表明库存增加和激烈的价格竞争正在削弱汽车行业押注其未来的技术市场。</p><p>福特汽车公司周一表示，此次降价实际上使 Lightning 的起价下降了近 10,000 美元，至 49,995 美元，原因是材料成本降低以及该公司工厂产量增加。某些版本的降价幅度会比其他版本更大。</p><p> Lightning是福特迄今为止最引人注目的电动汽车产品之一，也是其增长计划的关键，因为该公司旨在将更多产品线从继续为其大部分利润带来的汽油动力汽车转型。</p><p>全球汽车制造商一直在投资数千亿美元来创造新的电动车型、建设电池工厂和建设新的电动汽车工厂。多年来<span class="company-name-type">，在</span><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="">特斯拉</a>股价迅速上涨后，资本狂潮在一定程度上是由收紧碳排放要求引发的，激发了寻求<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-problem-with-teslas-ai-rally-in-eight-charts-e72dbb8f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">增长</a>机会的投资者的热情。</p><p>一路走来，汽车行业高管一直宣称消费者对他们最新的电动汽车产品表现出浓厚的兴趣，因为这些公司制定了将其产品线转变为电动汽车的雄心勃勃的目标。现在，福特的闪电降价是最新的进展，引发了人们对新兴电动汽车市场实力的质疑。</p><p>电动汽车的整体销售速度虽然比整体汽车市场强劲得多，但今年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ev-sales-growth-in-first-half-slows-from-torrid-pace-2bd2790e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">上半年有所放缓</a>。与此同时，一些汽车公司已经报告库存过剩，这与一年前的情况相反，当时许多新发布的车型都有数月的等待名单。</p><p>一些汽车制造商也一直在降低最畅销的电动汽车车型的价格。</p><p>根据 Motor Intelligence 的数据，特斯拉今年截至 6 月份在美国电动汽车市场的份额为 60%。该公司报告称，得益于今年早些时候推出的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-cuts-prices-again-as-it-seeks-to-lure-new-buyers-bc8394e5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">大幅降价</a>和折扣<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-deliveries-to-show-whether-price-cuts-are-paying-off-2f2aac93?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，第二季度的交付量激增</a>。同样在周末，特斯拉在原型车推出近四年后<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-begins-cybertruck-production-after-yearslong-wait-dbff33f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">开始生产</a>其 Cyber​​truck。</p><p>福特在一月份<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-cuts-prices-of-ev-mustang-mach-e-11675090387?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">回应特斯拉降价，</a>降低了其野马 Mach-E 电动 SUV 的价格，该 SUV 是特斯拉最畅销的 Model Y 的直接竞争对手。这家位于密歇根州迪尔伯恩的汽车公司在 2019 年再次降低了 Mach-E 的价格。可能。</p><p>首次推出时，Lightning 的起价约为 40,000 美元。然而，在需求强劲期间，福特多次<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-raises-price-again-on-electric-f-150-lightning-truck-fe0010ea?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">提高了标价</a>，以帮助抵消与材料和电池投入相关的更高费用。</p><p>在电动皮卡降价的消息传出后，福特股价周一下跌 5.9%。</p><p>福特首席执行官吉姆·法利</p>对电动汽车降价保持沉默，理由是担心这会损害转售价值和品牌形象。福特在过去一年中之所以能够提高 Lightning 的价格，部分原因是市场上的电动卡车选择很少。<p></p><p> “我们能走多远是有限的，”法利在五月份的《华尔街日报》活动中谈到该公司的降价策略时说道。 “我认为这是一个令人担忧的趋势。”</p><p>由于一些汽车制造商效仿特斯拉的做法，电动汽车定价全年都在走软。研究公司 Cox Automotive 的数据显示，从 2022 年 6 月到上个月，整个行业购买者为电动汽车支付的平均价格下降了近 20%。汽油发动机汽车的价格同期保持稳定，小幅上涨至 48,808 美元。</p><p>电动汽车已开始在美国经销商处销售。 Cox 表示，截至 6 月底，电动汽车库存尚有 92 天未售出，这是根据近期销售趋势衡量库存可用性的指标，而所有类型车辆的供应量为 51 天。</p><p>库存数据不包括直接向消费​​者销售的特斯拉。第一季度，特斯拉制成品的价值（反映未售出的车辆库存和正在运送给客户的车辆以及其他可供销售的产品的指标）从前一年的不到 10 亿美元增加到约 46 亿美元，证券文件显示。</p><p>由于福特的目标是大幅增加产量，因此提高电动卡车的销量变得更加重要。过去几年，福特两次提高了 Lightning 工厂的产量目标，现在的目标是在底特律郊区的工厂每年生产约 15 万辆电动卡车。</p><p>特斯拉也致力于提高电动汽车的生产速度，最近申请批准将其位于柏林附近的工厂规模扩大一倍，以便每年生产多达 100 万辆电动汽车。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=DA8844A5-F592-400E-8432-35B615313E7B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fford-cuts-price-of-ev-f-150-lightning-truck-by-up-to-17-2cc21c6a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">特斯拉大幅降价数周后，福特汽车也降低了其电动野马 Mach-E 的价格。 《华尔街日报》汽车记者诺拉·埃克特 (Nora Eckert) 比较了汽车制造商的战略举措，并解释了这对行业意味着什么。插图：Josephine Chu<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>汽车行业面临着销售更多电动汽车的压力，部分原因是美国、欧洲和中国的政府监管更加严格。拜登政府于 4 月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/epa-seeks-to-boost-evs-with-toughest-ever-rules-on-tailpipe-emissions-5658217d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">提出了美国有史以来最严格的汽车污染限制措施</a>，并制定了新规则，分析人士称，到 2032 年，所有销售的新车中约三分之二是电动汽车。</p><p>福特在其销售的电动汽车上已经出现亏损。该公司预计这部分业务今年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-projects-3-billion-loss-on-ev-business-for-2023-98037e4e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">可能损失 30 亿美元</a>，预计这一数字将被其燃气发动机业务赚取的利润所抵消。</p><p>特斯拉继续主导全球电动汽车市场，一直积极努力增加销量，即使这是以牺牲<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-tsla-q1-earnings-report-2023-6b441d30?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">近期盈利能力</a>为代价的。</p><p>全年，该公司发布了一系列价格调整，有效地将车辆成本降低了 14% 至 28%（具体取决于车型）。特斯拉<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/teslas-price-cuts-are-roiling-the-car-market-11674327793?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">有更大的降价空间</a>，因为其营业利润率高于包括福特在内的竞争对手。</p><p>今年上半年，美国全行业电动汽车销量猛增 50%，较去年同期 71% 的增幅有所回落。</p><p>福特的电动汽车销量今年上半年增长了 12%，但高管们表示，如果生产 Mach-E 和 F-150 Lightning 的两家工厂没有因扩张而暂时关闭，增长率会更高。</p><p> <em>——威尔·福尔 (Will Feuer) 对本文做出了贡献</em>。</p><p>写信给诺拉·埃克特 (Nora Eckert)，邮箱为<a href="mailto:nora.eckert@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">nora.eckert@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 21:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-cuts-price-of-ev-f-150-lightning-truck-by-up-to-17-2cc21c6a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-cuts-price-of-ev-f-150-lightning-truck-by-up-to-17-2cc21c6a<author><![CDATA[Nora Eckert]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>机动车</category><category>乘用车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category><category>容量/设施</category><category>价格</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>市场/营销</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>福特汽车</category><category>F</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>福特</category><category>吉姆·法利</category><category>容量</category><category>设施</category><category>价格</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>市场</category><category>营销</category><category>机动车</category><category>乘用车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Tesla Outlines Plan to Create Largest Auto Factory in Germany]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>电动汽车制造商计划将柏林地区工厂的产能翻一番，达到每年 100 万辆汽车<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060669"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="589" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818382?width=860&amp;height=589" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">这家电动汽车制造商已申请批准扩建其位于东部勃兰登堡州的现有工厂。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Patrick Pleul/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060669"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/william-boston" itemprop="url" rel="author">威廉·波士顿</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 5:01（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-outlines-plan-to-create-largest-auto-factory-in-germany-4aaea3bc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>柏林——<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="company-name">特斯拉</a>计划将其柏林附近工厂的规模扩大一倍，每年生产多达 100 万辆电动汽车，这一扩张可能使该工厂成为德国最大的汽车制造工厂。</p><p>根据最近几天向当地官员提交的文件，这家电动汽车制造商已申请批准扩建其位于东部勃兰登堡州的现有工厂，以提高车辆和电池的产能。</p><p>特斯拉已获得对工厂进行一些改造的初步批准，但全面批准仍需等待环境影响研究的完成，该研究将取决于当地居民的意见。当地官员将从本周起在网上发布特斯拉的申请，当地居民将有机会提出反对意见。十月份可能会举行公开听证会来讨论任何问题。</p><p>当特斯拉最初建造工厂时，环保组织放慢了进程，因为他们与该公司就该工厂对当地森林和野生动物的潜在影响以及该工厂将从当地水源排出的水量进行了斗争。新的应用程序也可能面临类似的阻力。</p><p>为了解决潜在的环境问题，特斯拉发言人表示，扩建不需要从当地来源额外提供淡水，因为该工厂拥有回收废水的设施，可以为增加产量提供额外的水。</p><p>该发言人补充说，拟议的扩建将使工厂的员工人数从目前的 10,000 多人增加到约 22,500 人。</p><p>特斯拉去年初开始在德国首都郊区的工厂生产 Model Y。根据消费者研究组织 Jato Dynamics 的数据，这款广受欢迎的全电动 SUV 是第一季度欧洲最畅销的汽车。今年 3 月，特斯拉在推特上<a href="https://twitter.com/Tesla/status/1639713037174161408" target="_blank" class="icon none">表示</a>，该工厂每周的产量已达到 5,000 辆。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="506" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818381?width=700&amp;height=506" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">特斯拉去年初开始在德国首都郊区的工厂生产 Model Y。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：肖恩·盖洛普/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><a href="https://www.jato.com/tesla-model-y-becomes-europes-best-selling-car-for-q1-2023/" target="_blank" class="icon none">尽管</a>特斯拉的整体销量与德国大型汽车品牌相比仍相形见绌，但特斯拉的 Model Y 和 Model 3 是第一季度欧洲最畅销的全电动汽车，轻松超过<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/XE/XETR/VOW" class="">大众</a><span class="company-name-type">的</span>ID.3 和 ID.4。 <a href="https://www.jato.com/tesla-model-y-becomes-europes-best-selling-car-for-q1-2023/" target="_blank" class="icon none">贾托</a>。</p><p>欧洲汽车协会的数据显示，今年前五个月，特斯拉在欧盟、其自由贸易联盟合作伙伴和英国销售了 138,294 辆新车，占该地区新车销量的份额达到 2.6%。制造商协会。这使得这家总部位于德克萨斯州奥斯汀的公司领先于日产和沃尔沃等老牌制造商。</p><p>欧洲电动汽车市场增速有所放缓，但销量增长依然强劲。制造商协会的数据显示，最新可用数据显示，今年前五个月，欧盟、欧洲自由贸易联盟和英国的纯电动汽车销量增长了 42.3%，达到 730,137 辆。</p><p>该协会表示，5月份纯电动汽车占新车销量的近14%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="488" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818376?width=700&amp;height=488" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2022 年 3 月，特斯拉首席执行官埃隆·马斯克与德国总理奥拉夫·肖尔茨（最左边）以及戴眼镜的勃兰登堡州州长迪特马尔·沃德克在格伦海德的工厂。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社撰稿人#afp/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>德国 IG Metall 工会对特斯拉格伦海德工厂增加就业岗位的前景表示欢迎。不过，工会也指出，该公司已经解雇了部分员工和合同工。</p><p> “仅上个月就有近 200 名正式员工被解雇或签署了遣散协议，”IG Metall 柏林、勃兰登堡和萨克森地区经理 Dirk Schulze 表示。</p><p>特斯拉位于格伦海德的工厂没有成立工会，但 IG Metall 在工厂附近设有办事处，并在特斯拉员工中开展宣传活动。</p><p>写信给威廉·波士顿<a href="mailto:william.boston@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">william.boston@wsj.com</a></p><p id="correction" class="correction"><strong>更正和放大</strong><br>今年 3 月，特斯拉在推特上表示，该工厂每周的产量已达到 5,000 辆。本文的早期版本错误地称每天有 5,000 辆车。 （7月17日更正）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 21:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-outlines-plan-to-create-largest-auto-factory-in-germany-4aaea3bc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-outlines-plan-to-create-largest-auto-factory-in-germany-4aaea3bc<author><![CDATA[William Boston]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>机动车零件</category><category>汽车</category><category>输出/生产</category><category>容量/设施</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>输出</category><category>生产</category><category>容量</category><category>设施</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>服务</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>机动车辆零件</category><category>汽车</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Cathie Wood’s ARK Writes Down Twitter Stake by 47%]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>埃隆·马斯克的社交媒体公司正面临沉重的债务负担<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060482"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818488?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Cathie Wood 的 ARK Investment Management 通过其风险基金拥有 Twitter 的少量股份。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：大卫·斯旺森/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060482"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jack-pitcher" itemprop="url" rel="author">杰克·皮彻</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 4:23（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cathie-woods-ark-writes-down-twitter-stake-by-47-407b83d4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>伍德在接受采访时表示，自<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">埃隆·马斯克</a>去年将社交媒体公司 Twitter 私有化以来，凯西·伍德 (Cathie Wood) 旗下的 ARK Investment Management 已将其持有的 Twitter 股份减记了 47%。</p><p> “我们非常重视公平估值，绝对必须记下[Twitter]，”伍德周五表示。 “减记并不代表我们的基本面前景和对我们相信将为股东带来的长期投资回报的信念。”</p><p>伍德仍然看好 Twitter 的长期前景。她表示，她的基金经常更新私营公司的内部估值。</p><p> “实际上，我很想以这样的价格水平获得更多库存，但没有人愿意放弃任何库存。所以这告诉你一些事情，”她补充道。</p><p> ARK 通过其风险基金拥有 Twitter 的少量股份，该基金向公众开放，包括公开市场和私人投资。</p><p>在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/story/twitter-purchased-by-elon-musk-how-it-went-down-72a07de3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">马斯克进行 440 亿美元杠杆收购</a>后，Twitter 面临着沉重的债务负担和广告业务的急剧下降。马斯克周六<a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1680082007873953794?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1680082007873953794%7Ctwgr%5E4b0d552330bca5ec541f846f2df2a4fde28c3835%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Flivecoverage.dowjones.io%2Fwsj" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">在推文中表示，</a>广告收入下降了约 50%，公司现金流为负。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C88AF8C6-9381-4531-8397-8E3466D42127&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fcathie-woods-ark-writes-down-twitter-stake-by-47-407b83d4&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Twitter 所有者埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk) 和 Meta 首席执行官马克·扎克伯格 (Mark Zuckerberg) 已同意进行笼式比赛。肢体冲突可能是第一次，但《华尔街日报》的乔安娜·斯特恩在动作玩偶的帮助下解释了为什么这场科技斗殴实际上就像过去的硅谷争吵一样。照片插图：Kenny Wassus、Preston Jessee<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>该公司还面临新的微博应用程序 Threads 的威胁，该应用程序由<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta Platforms</a>于本月推出，是 Twitter 的直接竞争对手。 Twitter 声称 Meta <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-threads-instagram-twitter-competitor-c68714f7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">可能窃取了知识产权</a>，但 Meta 否认了这一点。与 Instagram 相关的 Threads 注册用户已超过 1 亿。</p><p> “我们认为它们可以共存，”伍德在谈到 Threads 和 Instagram 时说道。 “我认为 Threads 点燃了竞争之火，或者将其提升了一个档次，这对 Twitter 来说是件好事。我们还认为，从长远来看，埃隆和团队非常认真地将其变成一个一切应用程序。”</p><p>马斯克表示，收购 Twitter <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/twitter-musk-deal/card/musk-tweets-that-twitter-deal-could-expedite-his-x-endeavor-tVWFtsAilBnDMMc9ZrAJ?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将帮助他创建“一款无所不包的应用程序”</a> ，将信息与娱乐结合起来，如果成功，将在 5 到 10 年内增长到超过 10 亿用户。</p><p>包括富达投资 (Fidelity Investments) 在内的其他资产管理公司已大幅减记其 Twitter 投资。根据每月披露的信息，截至 4 月 28 日，富达<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/twitter-is-now-worth-a-third-of-what-musk-paid-for-it-fidelity-says-e66f61db?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">投资对 Twitter 的估值是马斯克支付的三分之一</a>。</p><p>写信给杰克·皮彻<a href="mailto:jack.pitcher@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jack.pitcher@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 20:23:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/cathie-woods-ark-writes-down-twitter-stake-by-47-407b83d4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/cathie-woods-ark-writes-down-twitter-stake-by-47-407b83d4<author><![CDATA[Jack Pitcher]]></author><category>专有的</category><category>金融投资服务</category><category>投资建议/研究服务</category><category>金融服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台/工具</category><category>技术</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>产品/服务中断</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>推特</category><category>TWTR.XX</category><category>凯西·伍德</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>服务</category><category>产品</category><category>服务中断</category><category>金融投资服务</category><category>投资建议</category><category>研究服务</category><category>金融服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>投资</category><category>证券</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台</category><category>工具</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Efforts to Rein In AI Tap Lesson From Social Media: Don’t Wait Until It’s Too Late]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>活动人士和官员竞相制定规则和公众对新人工智能工具的理解<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817815/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>斯蒂芬妮·阿伦森/《华尔街日报》；照片：iStock <span>Stephanie Aaronson/华尔街日报；照片：iStock</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001055980"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001055980"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/deepa-seetharaman" itemprop="url" rel="author">迪帕·西塔拉曼</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 1:53（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/efforts-to-rein-in-ai-tap-lesson-from-social-media-dont-wait-until-its-too-late-d6d3fb49"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>在认真开始遏制其不良影响的努力之前，社交媒体已有十多年的历史。有了人工智能，立法者、活动人士和高管就不会等待那么久了。</p><p>在过去的几个月里，屡获殊荣的科学家、白宫官员和科技首席执行官呼吁对生成式人工智能工具（例如由<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>支持的初创公司 OpenAI <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-ai-chatbot-app-explained-11675865177?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">去年推出的聊天机器人 ChatGPT）</a>采取防护措施。与会人员中有许多为让社交媒体更安全<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-new-tech-avengers-1530285064?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">而持续奋斗的资深人士</a>。</p><p>这些倡导者认为人工智能辩论是一个新的机会，可以影响公司如何制造和营销其产品，并塑造公众对该技术的期望。他们的目标是更快地塑造人工智能格局，并从社交媒体之争中的错误中吸取教训。</p><p> “我们错过了社交媒体的窗口期，”儿童互联网安全组织 Common Sense Media 的首席执行官吉姆·斯泰尔 (Jim Steyer) 表示，多年来，该组织一直在隐私和有害内容等问题上批评社交媒体平台。 “已经晚了——非常晚了——基本规则已经制定，行业就可以做任何它想做的事。”</p><p>活动人士和高管都在推出一系列项目和提案，以形成理解和监管，以解决人工智能潜在的操纵、错误信息和偏见等问题。</p><p> Common Sense 正在开发一个独立的人工智能评级和评论系统，该系统将评估 ChatGPT 等人工智能产品对私人数据的处理、是否适合儿童以及其他因素。该非营利组织计划于今年秋季启动该系统，除了 2500 万美元的预算外，每年还将花费 500 万至 1000 万美元来资助该项目。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=EC817295-03D0-4031-B40B-694D7BDE2797&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fefforts-to-rein-in-ai-tap-lesson-from-social-media-dont-wait-until-its-too-late-d6d3fb49&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">新的人工智能语音和视频工具看起来和听起来都像你。但它们能骗过你的家人或银行吗？ 《华尔街日报》的乔安娜·斯特恩 (Joanna Stern) 当天用她的人工智能双胞胎代替了自己，以找出答案。图片插图：埃琳娜·斯科蒂<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>包括 Mozilla 基金会在内的其他互联网倡导团体也在构建自己的开源人工智能工具，并投资于自称正在构建负责任的人工智能系统的初创公司。一些最初专注于社交媒体的公司现在正试图向人工智能公司出售服务，以帮助他们的聊天机器人避免大量传播错误信息和其他有害内容。</p><p>科技公司正在竞相影响监管，与对人工智能持谨慎态度并渴望利用其机遇的全球政府进行讨论。 5月初，拜登总统在白宫会见了OpenAI、微软、谷歌等公司首席执行官。 OpenAI 首席执行官 Sam Altman 花了数周时间<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-owner-vows-to-improve-its-ai-tools-after-sam-altmans-world-tour-e0466dfd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与全球立法者和其他领导人会面</a>，讨论人工智能的风险以及公司的安全监管理念。</p><p>奥特曼和微软总裁布拉德·史密斯都<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpts-sam-altman-faces-senate-panel-examining-artificial-intelligence-4bb6942a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">主张建立</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsofts-president-backs-new-agency-to-regulate-chatgpt-other-ai-systems-c847bae0" target="_blank" class="icon none">一个新的监管机构</a>来授权大型人工智能系统。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="company-name">特斯拉</a>首席执行官<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">埃隆·马斯克</a>，</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-xai-artificial-intelligence-company-openai-chatgpt-4a6f178a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">周三，他宣布</a>正式启动<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-new-artificial-intelligence-business-x-ai-incorporates-in-nevada-962c7c2f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">新的人工智能初创公司</a>，并于 5 月表示，政府应召集一个独立的监督委员会，其中可能包括行业高管，以制定确保人工智能安全开发的规则。<p></p><p>联邦贸易委员会也在认真审视人工智能。根据上周公布的民事传票<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-under-investigation-by-ftc-21e4b3ef?mod=hp_lead_pos2&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，该公司正在调查 OpenAI 是否</a>因 ChatGPT 发布的虚假信息而“从事不公平或欺骗性行为”。 Altman 表示，OpenAI 有信心遵守法律，“我们当然会与 FTC 合作。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>在所有这些活动中，许多活动人士和立法者越来越感到，多年来监管或以其他方式改变社交媒体公司（包括 Facebook 母公司 Meta Platforms、Twitter 和 TikTok）的努力并不令人满意。 Facebook 成立于 2004 年，Twitter 成立于 2006 年，但直到俄罗斯干预以及 2016 年美国大选的其他问题被发现后，有关监管的广泛讨论才真正开始。</p><p> “国会未能在社交媒体上迎接这一时刻，”民主党参议员理查德·布卢门撒尔 (Richard Blumenthal)</p>五月份在国会关于人工智能的听证会上说道。 “现在我们有义务在威胁和风险成为现实之前在人工智能上做到这一点。”<p></p><p>尽管近年来社交媒体高管呼吁加强监管，但美国尚未制定新的联邦法律来要求公司保护用户的隐私和数据，也没有更新近三十年的平台内容监管规则。部分原因是立法者之间存在分歧，即企业是否应该采取更多措施来调节其平台上的言论，或者是否已经越界到扼杀言论自由的地步。</p><p>一些经历过这些斗争的活动人士表示，这个时代的两个主要教训是，不能相信这些公司能够自我监管，而且联邦政府陷入僵局，无法通过有意义的立法。 “存在巨大的空白，”常识媒体的斯泰尔说。</p><p>然而，他和其他人表示，人工智能公司愿意讨论重大问题，这让他们感到鼓舞。</p><p> “我们看到来自社交媒体的信任和安全团队的一些人现在已经在人工智能公司工作了，”说</p>L. Gordon Crovitz，NewsGuard 的联合创始人，这是一家跟踪和评价新闻网站的公司。 《华尔街日报》前出版人克罗维茨表示，这些人在目前的角色中似乎拥有更多权力。 “肢体语言是‘我们被释放了。’”<p></p><p> GPT-4 等大型语言模型是根据可以从互联网上抓取的任何内容进行训练的，但这些数据包含大量仇恨言论、错误信息和其他有害内容。因此，这些模型在初始训练后会进一步完善，以在称为微调的过程中剔除一些不良内容。</p><p> NewsGuard 一直在与人工智能公司讨论许可其数据（克罗维茨称之为“现有的所有重要虚假叙述的目录”）的事宜，以进行微调并加强人工智能模型的防护，防止产生此类错误信息和虚假信息。叙述。</p><p> Ravi Iyer 是 Meta 的前产品经理，现在在南加州大学马歇尔商学院工作，正在开发一项民意调查，跟踪人们如何体验人工智能系统。他希望这项民意调查能够影响人工智能公司设计和部署其产品的方式。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您希望看到哪些法规或标准应用于 ChatGPT 等生成式 AI 服务？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “我们需要知道这是平台可以做出的选择，并奖励他们没有做出错误的选择，”艾耶说。</p><p>开发 Firefox 互联网浏览器的非营利组织 Mozilla 基金会表示，它正在构建开源模型，作为大型私人人工智能模型的替代品。 “我们需要建立替代方案，而不仅仅是倡导它们，”Mozilla 总裁马克·苏尔曼 (Mark Surman) 表示。</p><p> Steyer 将 Common Sense 正在构建的人工智能评级系统描述为该非营利组织历史上最雄心勃勃的系统。曾在谷歌工作并正在帮助构建该系统的顾问特雷西·皮佐·弗雷 (Tracy Pizzo Frey) 表示，没有固定的方法来评估人工智能工具的安全性。</p><p>到目前为止，Common Sense 正在考虑七个因素，包括公司对其系统功能的透明度以及仍然存在的缺陷。该非营利组织可能会考虑公司提供多少有关其训练数据的信息，包括 OpenAI 在内的公司将这些信息视为竞争秘密。</p><p>弗雷表示，Common Sense 不会要求提供专有数据，但需要帮助家长和教育工作者就人工智能的使用做出明智决定的信息。 “对于透明度是什么样的，没有任何规则，”弗雷说。</p><p>写信给 Deepa Seetharaman，电子邮件地址： <a href="mailto:deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/45b711d0-d12b-4ed4-89ff-24783c6b1fa4.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 17:53:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/efforts-to-rein-in-ai-tap-lesson-from-social-media-dont-wait-until-its-too-late-d6d3fb49</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/efforts-to-rein-in-ai-tap-lesson-from-social-media-dont-wait-until-its-too-late-d6d3fb49<author><![CDATA[Deepa Seetharaman]]></author><category> WSJ插画</category><category>WSJ公司</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>微软</category><category>微软公司</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ukrainian Strike Disables Bridge Between Crimea and Russia]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>俄罗斯称基辅使用海军无人机仅袭击了从半岛到俄罗斯的公路<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059347"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=562ED18C-1F7B-4F97-8EEF-A3B2EE57B4D8&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fbridge-between-russia-and-crimea-damaged-in-overnight-strike-a3431b88&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">连接俄罗斯和被占领的克里米亚半岛的刻赤大桥在乌克兰的一次袭击中被毁。俄罗斯表示，基辅使用两架海军无人机袭击了这座桥，该桥是为在乌克兰作战的俄罗斯军队提供补给的重要路线。照片：CRIMEA24TV/路透社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059347"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/yaroslav-trofimov" itemprop="url" rel="author">雅罗斯拉夫·特罗菲莫夫</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 17 日上午 9:23（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bridge-between-russia-and-crimea-damaged-in-overnight-strike-a3431b88"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>乌克兰的一次袭击使连接俄罗斯与被占领的克里米亚半岛的唯一公路桥瘫痪，再次打击了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京</a>总统统治的一个主要象征，并限制了俄罗斯对乌克兰南部<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-war-counteroffensive-frontlines-russia-add3e4e4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">前线的</a>供应。</p><p>俄罗斯国家反恐委员会表示，基辅当地时间周一凌晨 3 点左右使用两架海军无人机袭击了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/attack-on-russias-kerch-bridge-hits-crucial-link-for-crimea-and-troops-11665342526?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">这座桥</a>。乌克兰媒体援引政府消息人士的话称，海军无人机也参与其中。</p><p>乌克兰 SBU 情报部门发言人 Artem Degtyarenko 告诉乌克兰国际文传电讯社，有关袭击组织方式的所有细节将在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-gears-up-to-hit-russiansand-show-west-it-can-win-89c43105?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰获胜</a>后公布。总统弗拉基米尔·泽连斯基的顾问米哈伊洛·波多利亚克表示：“任何用于运送俄罗斯大规模谋杀工具的非法建筑都必然是短暂的。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="908" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/d0587735-f4b2-487c-afa7-3aaa47c344b7-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>从刻赤大桥拍摄的视频显示，该大桥全长 12 英里，耗资 40 亿美元建造，该大桥的西行跨度倒塌，平行的东行跨度移位。这意味着这条重要动脉的交通可能需要几周甚至几个月的时间才能恢复。一座对于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-says-it-is-boosting-military-production-as-campaign-in-ukraine-stalls-a4b19dcd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">军事补给</a>更为重要的独立铁路桥完好无损。刻赤海峡的铁路交通周一恢复。</p><p>俄罗斯副总理马拉特·库斯努林表示，俄罗斯将组织途经乌克兰南部被占领地区的替代道路连接，沿线宵禁将取消，边境检查将放松。他说，工程师已经在检查桥梁的损坏情况：“到晚上，有关条款和修复桥梁的可能性的情况就会清楚。”官员称，重要物资将通过渡轮运往<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-finds-a-new-target-maps-that-still-mark-crimea-as-ukraines-11673521246?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">半岛</a>。</p><p>俄罗斯表示，两名平民在袭击中死亡，并指责基辅犯有恐怖主义行为。俄罗斯执政党主席、普京副国家安全顾问、前总统德米特里·梅德韦杰夫表示，应对此次袭击负责的乌克兰官员及其亲属的住宅应被炸毁以示报复。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818349?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一架军用直升机飞越刻赤大桥受损部分。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>乌克兰上个月在乌克兰南部发动攻势，但由于其部队面临大片雷区和防御工事以及俄罗斯武装直升机，因此只取得了有限的进展。最近几周，基辅利用英国和法国提供的“风暴之影”和“头皮” <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-deadly-new-missile-was-created-to-hit-saddam-hussein-in-his-bathtub-75e04412" target="_blank" class="icon none">巡航导弹</a>，大大扩展了其射程，重点摧毁俄罗斯武器库、指挥中心和后勤节点。</p><p>上个月，“风暴之影”袭击了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-strikes-bridge-supplying-russian-troops-56564b0b" target="_blank" class="icon none">琼哈尔大桥，</a>克里米亚和乌克兰南部之间的主要连接被切断了十天，这条替代道路现在已成为俄罗斯的主要生命线。琼哈尔大桥于7月3日重新开放。</p><p>去年秋天，乌克兰成功地运用了这一战略，当时对第聂伯河上的桥梁和其他后勤节点的袭击将俄罗斯军队赶出了被占领的南部城市赫尔松。</p><p>周一的袭击发生当天，俄罗斯、土耳其、联合国和乌克兰之间允许乌克兰港口出口谷物和其他食品的协议即将到期。该协议一年前在伊斯坦布尔达成，此后定期更新。袭击发生后，俄罗斯表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-says-it-is-pulling-out-of-ukraine-grain-deal-68190d1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将退出该协议</a>，但谈判仍在继续，土耳其总统雷杰普·塔伊普·埃尔多安表示，他计划与普京讨论延期事宜。 Ukraine exported more than 32 million tons of food since the agreement took effect last August. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818163?width=700&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> This image reportedly shows damage to the bridge connecting Russia to Crimea.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: OSTOROZHNO NOVOSTI/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Unlike Monday&#39;s strike, an attack by Ukraine on the Kerch Bridge in October also temporarily disabled the rail bridge, with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/major-explosion-hits-the-bridge-between-crimea-and-russia-halting-traffic-11665215052?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">several fuel cars catching fire</a> . However, only one section of the four-lane road bridge was destroyed at the time and car traffic resumed on the remaining two lanes shortly thereafter. The road bridge was fully repaired by the end of February.</p><p> Putin responded to the October attack by ordering waves of strikes on Ukrainian civilian infrastructure that <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-ukraine-survived-russias-mission-to-turn-off-the-lights-winter-is-over-and-were-still-here-8668c5f5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">aimed to deprive Ukrainians</a> of electricity, heating and water during the winter. Those barrages, while causing rolling blackouts, ultimately failed to destroy the country&#39;s energy system while prompting the US and allies to supply Ukraine with modern air defenses, such as Patriot and SAMP-T antimissile systems.</p><p> The Kerch Bridge was meant to be a symbol of Russia&#39;s permanent control over Crimea, a peninsula annexed by Putin in 2014 in what Russian propaganda has praised as one of his most lasting achievements. Crimea is now in full tourist season, and tens of thousands of tourists are stranded there with their vehicles.</p><p> Civilian air connections to Crimea ceased in February last year, as Putin launched the invasion of Ukraine. Alternative connections to Russia through the rutted roads of occupied parts of southern Ukraine&#39;s Kherson, Zaporizhzhia and Donetsk regions are complicated, and in some parts run relatively close to the front line. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="435" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818168?width=700&amp;height=435" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Police officers block a road leading to a bridge across the Kerch Strait following a traffic suspension.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Sergei Malgavko/TASS/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Write to Yaroslav Trofimov at <a href="mailto:yaroslav.trofimov@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">yaroslav.trofimov@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 13:23:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bridge-between-russia-and-crimea-damaged-in-overnight-strike-a3431b88</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bridge-between-russia-and-crimea-damaged-in-overnight-strike-a3431b88<author><![CDATA[Yaroslav Trofimov]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>海军</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>弗拉基米尔普京</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>海军</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Divorce Parties Are a New Hot Invite. ‘It Sort of Ended Up as a Really Fun Funeral.’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> With society widely accepting of broken marriages, many newly uncoupled people feel emboldened to throw themselves bashes; &#39;End of an error&#39; <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-814552?width=1000&amp;height=562" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Video: Vasya Kolotusha <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001042895"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001042895"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lane-florsheim" itemprop="url" rel="author">Lane Florsheim</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 17, 2023 7:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/divorce-parties-registries-marriage-1ed745b9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web
          bigtophero
"></div><p> After Brandi Stellers finalized her divorce, she invited close friends to a soiree in May. She mixed signature cocktails, hung a “Bye Felicia” banner and handed out fake rose petals to toss in the air.</p><p> Party decorations included a photo of a pair of penguins, torn down the middle.</p><p> “I ripped the penguins in half because penguins are monogamous birds who are supposed to mate for life,” she says. “Well, I&#39;m not your penguin anymore.”</p><p> The newly uncoupled are throwing themselves blowout bashes to mark their liberation from unhappy marriages, almost like reverse bachelorette parties. “I wanted to celebrate not a divorce, but a new chapter, with people whom I love who want the best for me,” says Stellers, who works at a cloud-computing company in Columbus, Ohio. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="803" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817952?width=639&amp;height=803" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Brandi Stellers at her post-divorce soiree.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Brandi Stellers</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> For most of history, divorce hasn&#39;t been an event touted to the world. Now, a culture shift is under way. The US divorce rate has been dipping, but those who get them feel freer to trumpet their breakups. The number of American adults who consider divorce to be morally acceptable has hit historic highs, according to Gallup polls.</p><p> “Divorce used to be something to be ashamed of due to societal pressures and stereotypes,” says Nicole Sodoma, a divorce lawyer who wrote the book “Please Don&#39;t Say You&#39;re Sorry” about the topic. “But today people have really decided to nip that societal shame and instead embrace being divorced as another stage of life that some of us experience.”</p><p> On <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ETSY" class="company-name">Etsy</a> and Amazon, brands sell splitsville swag, including “End of an Error” sashes, “Thank U Next” rose-gold foil balloons, and “I do.我做到了。 I&#39;m done” T-shirts. On <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PINS" class="">Pinterest</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> the online platform for sharing creative ideas, “search trends show that people are gaining a new perspective of divorce,” says Swasti Sarna, Global Director of Data Insights at Pinterest.</p><p> Pinterest searches for “divorce-party games” surged 80%, and searches for “divorce cakes” rose 50% in June 2022 from a year earlier. There were also jumps in searches for divorce-party decorating ideas (35%) and for “divorce gifts” (30%), according to Pinterest.</p><p> “It was just this feeling of, I&#39;m not ashamed of this,” says Nadine Adamson, a real-estate broker in Manhattan and Brooklyn who had a divorce party. “I think being married for more than 10 years in New York—I was married for 12—is a huge success.”</p><p> Adamson had friends from Los Angeles fly to New York and they booked the hotel suite where she had stayed when she got married. “It felt like closure in a really beautiful way to be in the same hotel with the same view,” she says.</p><p> The four of them burned sage in the suite, to rid it of negative vibes, filled the place with balloons, dined out and then had a sleepover. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="696" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817050?width=700&amp;height=696" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Nadine Adamson at her divorce party, at the hotel room where she stayed for her wedding.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Christa Renee</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Adamson also continues to post on Instagram with the hashtag #divorceparty, not because she keeps throwing them, but as a way to highlight her new life, such as upgrading her brownstone with a cozy wood-burning fireplace.</p><p> “I guess divorce parties are a thing?” a Reddit user wrote a few months ago in a post that drew nearly 4,000 comments. The poster included a photo of an invitation from a divorcing couple that was throwing a joint party. “Plus ones are welcome—ours will be there!” it said.</p><p> Kris Marks, a mental-health facilitator in Alberta, Canada, says he initially felt conflicted when a friend invited him to celebrate a divorce. Marks was also friends with the ex-husband, and didn&#39;t think he knew about the party.</p><p> “I had so many thoughts, like, should we be celebrating the end of a commitment?” Marks says. “I went back and forth and I came to the conclusion that yes, the institution of marriage is what it is, but if you&#39;re choosing to move on from it, that&#39;s a hard thing to do and a fresh start should be celebrated. I was kind of all for it.”</p><p> His friend, who was married for 12 years, threw a potluck dinner and then the group went out for a night on the town. “It was me and another guy and maybe 10 women and it was like being a fly on the wall at a bachelorette party,” he says. Marks bought his friend a month of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dating-apps-paid-memberships-tinder-raya-hinge-11664984612?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Bumble Premium</a> as a present.</p><p> Some businesses cater to newly uncoupled men. Stripe Street Studio, a design firm founded in 2020, for instance, specializes in helping divorced and single men set up homes. On Pinterest, searches for the now popular catchphrase “divorced dad aesthetic” were up nearly 300% in June from a year earlier, the company says.</p><p> Anecdotally, though, more women than men are holding outright divorce bashes.</p><p> “As a guy, we don&#39;t call it a divorce party, we call it &#39;Let&#39;s go for drinks,” reasons Marks. “We just cope differently.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817046?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> When Nicole Sodoma got divorced, she bought a vintage car she named Stella after the 1998 rom-com &#39;How Stella Got Her Groove Back.&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Darius Evans/DME Imagery</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> One can now find registry sites that help divorcées restock—since only one half of the couple gets the pasta maker, the spice rack or the Le Creuset cookware.</p><p> After Olivia Dreizen Howell separated in 2019, she stayed in the marital residence, which was suddenly much emptier. “Half of my stuff was gone,” she says, and other items were emotionally charged belongings from her wedding registry. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817051?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Olivia Dreizen Howell signing her divorce papers.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Fresh Starts Registry</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> So she and her sister Jenny Dreizen founded the website Fresh Starts in 2021 for people going through the same experience.</p><p> The company helps the newly unwed set up gift registries to restock specific rooms in their new homes. The most popular registry items are for kitchens and bathrooms. They also offer a network of experts, such as real-estate agents, forgiveness coaches, and a divorce doula who helps plan divorce parties.</p><p> Lizzie Post, the co-author of “Emily Post Etiquette: The Centennial Edition,” says the Emily Post Institute doesn&#39;t consider either divorce parties or post-divorce registries appropriate as of yet.</p><p> “Getting together with your friends after finalizing a divorce and finding a way to feel good about closing that chapter is a beautifully supportive thing,” she says. “I think calling it a divorce party feels a bit tactless.”</p><p> Allison McWhite, a legal assistant in New York, says planning her own divorce party ushered in a sense of control. “It seemed for a long time that something was happening to me, charging at me, as opposed to me handling it,” she says.</p><p> She threw her celebration at a friend&#39;s apartment, where music videos were projected onto a wall, black balloons littered the floor and candlesticks dripped wax onto the empty wine bottles that held them. A white cake proclaimed “Just Divorced” in cherry-red icing. McWhite wore a lacy sheer black dress, red lipstick and a fur coat in keeping with the party dress code of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/forget-wedding-dresses-divorce-style-has-arrived-11612616414?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">1950s divorcée chic</a> . (Think Marilyn Monroe&#39;s 1954 divorce from Joe DiMaggio in which she famously wore a little black dress, pumps and white gloves to the courthouse.) </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/9c101278-b1d5-4ed6-915b-14735a357de8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Guests danced into the wee hours and toasted the start of her new life.</p><p> “It sort of ended up as a really fun funeral,” McWhite says.</p><p> For some divorcées, trying to celebrate can backfire and feel like a reminder of the loss.</p><p> “When you get divorced, you kind of lose half your friends,” says Ayesha Vardag, a divorce lawyer in London whose friends encouraged her to have a party after her own divorce. At their insistence, she booked a nice room above a pub, where she says there was loud music and “a bit of dancing, but not enough, as there really weren&#39;t enough people.”</p><p> “It was just a huge pressure to be fun,” she says. “Afterward, I felt I should just allow myself to be really quite upset and come out of that slowly.”</p><p> Travel blogger Maja Proescholdt says her divorce process, done without lawyers, was lengthy enough that by the time the paperwork was done, much of her grief had settled and she was ready for a party.</p><p> Her sister supplied a crown and a “Finally Divorced” sash. The group went out dancing, where the club&#39;s DJ called out, “Let&#39;s have it for Maja&#39;s divorce party!”</p><p> “That was a top life moment for me,” she says.</p><p> Write to Lane Florsheim at <a href="mailto:lane.florsheim@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">lane.florsheim@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/7014063b-a894-4b50-b6a3-a3b3e88591aa.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/divorce-parties-registries-marriage-1ed745b9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/divorce-parties-registries-marriage-1ed745b9<author><![CDATA[Lane Florsheim]]></author><category> a-hed</category><category> wsjstyle</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>结婚/离婚</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>婚姻</category><category>离婚</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[CIOs Fear Affirmative Action Ruling Could Set Back Progress in Tech Diversity]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Executives are questioning what a landmark Supreme Court decision on college admissions means for diversity hiring efforts <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001052162"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816563?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Black employees accounted for 8% of the IT workforce in the US last year, according to IT trade group CompTIA.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alex Slitz/Associated Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001052162"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/belle-lin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Belle Lin</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 17, 2023 7:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cio-affirmative-action-ruling-could-set-back-progress-in-tech-diversity-359adeea"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Business technology leaders said that last month&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-rules-against-affirmative-action-c94b5a9c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Supreme Court&#39;s ruling</a> that colleges can&#39;t consider race in admissions policies could have a chilling effect on initiatives aimed at diversifying the information-technology workforce.</p><p> The court&#39;s decision is likely to alter the pipeline of diverse graduates entering the job market, they said, and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-workplace-affirmative-action-dei-3646683b" target="_blank" class="icon none">may introduce challenges</a> to companies&#39; existing hiring and promotion practices.</p><p> By removing race from college admission considerations, the pool of tech talent entering the workforce may not only be less diverse, it could also be smaller if underrepresented minorities don&#39;t see the field as a welcoming or viable option, those executive say. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816532?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Robert Scott, vice president of the Information Technology Senior Management Forum</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Information Technology Senior Management Forum</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “This, to me, is another pendulum swing,” said Robert Scott, vice president of the Information Technology Senior Management Forum, an executive development group focused on Black technology leaders, and dean of its Global Institute for Professional Development. “Those that are looking for an excuse to back off will back off” on diversity efforts, he said.</p><p> Adding to the pressure, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/republican-attorneys-general-warn-top-u-s-businesses-over-discrimination-1eb78d29?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">a group of Republican attorneys general issued a letter on Thursday</a> to the nation&#39;s largest companies warning them against race-based preferences in hiring, promotions and contracting, citing the recent affirmative action ruling.</p><p> Over the past decade, and especially over the past several years, many <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-talent-diversity-took-on-new-urgency-in-2020-11608640200?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">CIOs have helped to institute</a> or strengthen programs to increase the numbers of minorities and women in their departments and initiatives designed to retain and advance those groups. But progress has been slow.</p><p> “Apart from the Supreme Court&#39;s recent decision, diversity in tech long has been a challenge,” said Steve Watt, chief information officer at Westlake, Ohio-based Hyland Software. “We know there is more work to be done.”</p><p> Black employees accounted for 8% of the IT workforce in the US last year and represented 12% of the overall US workforce, according to IT trade group CompTIA, which based its analysis on data from the US Bureau of Labor Statistics. Latino employees made up about 8% of the IT workforce and 17% of the country&#39;s workforce in 2022.</p><p> According to 2022 census data, the Black community made up 13.6% of the US population, while the Latino community made up 19.1%.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Among IT leadership last year, 6% of CIOs or IT directors were Black and 8% were Latino, CompTIA found. That makes developing diverse IT leaders, who typically hold advanced college degrees, even more critical, ITSMF&#39;s Scott said. “It&#39;s more likely that somebody can compete for those top-level C-suite jobs, if they&#39;ve gone through a more traditional path of growth and development,” he said.</p><p> “Many companies and leaders have embraced the need for diversity,” said Prasad Ramakrishnan, CIO of San Mateo, Calif.-based software maker <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/FRSH" class="">Freshworks</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> “This said, there could be a downstream impact on the workforce of the future if companies don&#39;t maintain the programs that are in place.”</p><p> The court&#39;s ruling came amid a complex hiring environment for tech talent. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/not-a-tech-firm-snaring-top-laid-off-tech-talent-wont-be-easy-7a6fdb2c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Laid-off workers from Big Tech firms</a> haven&#39;t necessarily been looking for IT roles at nontech companies. And amid continued cost cutting, US employers <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/employers-slash-it-jobs-in-june-9b0c9611?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">slashed IT jobs</a> last month.</p><p> Yet there remain over 120,000 unfilled IT roles due to lack of qualified candidates, according to consulting firm Janco Associates, with the greatest demand in areas <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazons-security-chief-keeps-focus-on-recruiting-and-retaining-talent-11670883520?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">such as cybersecurity</a> and software development.</p><p> “Whether or not there are affirmative action programs at universities or [diversity, equity and inclusion] programs at companies, the stark reality is that US businesses and the public sector are faced with a major talent shortage in critical areas,” said</p> Thomas Phelps IV, CIO of software firm Laserfiche. “It&#39;s critical to have a diverse, qualified candidate pool to help address our IT talent shortages.”<p></p><p> “I worry about, in universities, if we&#39;re not making it a more hospitable environment, that we make it harder than it is,” said Sharon Mandell, CIO of networking and cybersecurity firm <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JNPR" class="">Juniper Networks</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> That means companies and IT leaders need to work to convince diverse workers that technology is “a compelling place, and a welcome place for them.”</p><p> At the moment, many CIOs said they have no plans to dismantle existing diversity initiatives in their own companies or IT departments, though some say <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/companiesexpectnew-challenges-todiversitypolicies-after-court-ruling-4bf48c1d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the decision will require them to explain</a> why such programs are important to company performance. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816527?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Amplitude CIO Chetna Mahajan</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Amplitude</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> With improvement in internal diversity metrics, “we can tie it to our business outcomes,” said</p> Chetna Mahajan, CIO of San Francisco-based digital analytics company Amplitude. “The research is there, the data is there, so it&#39;s just making it customized to our company.”<p></p><p> Amplitude said Black employees account for 3% of its 700 workers this year, and Latino employees make up 5% of its workforce. In nontechnical positions, which include all departments outside of engineering and product development, 5% of employees are Black and 7% Latino.</p><p> Franklin Reed, executive director of global inclusion, diversity and equity at IT staffing and services firm TEKsystems, said some companies have pulled back on DEI efforts because they haven&#39;t been able to connect diversity initiatives with both “soft and hard” business metrics such as employee retention, engagement and revenue.</p><p> For the most part, the firm&#39;s corporate clients have said they will “stay the course” in DEI efforts following the Supreme Court ruling, he said. But the IT industry at-large has yet to fully recognize the effect the ruling could have on corporate DEI and hiring efforts, he said. “There&#39;s this assumption that it was the education industry, and we&#39;re business.”</p><p> Some companies have already said they are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-workplace-affirmative-action-dei-3646683b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">encountering resistance from employees</a> regarding diversity programs and reducing their investment in DEI in a sluggish economy. Mentions of social-impact initiatives like diversity during earnings calls have <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/executives-quiet-their-sustainability-talk-on-earnings-calls-amid-growing-culture-war-3a358c1f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">fallen off sharply in recent quarters</a> —reversing the trend of previous years.</p><p> That, in turn, has put more pressure on CIOs to keep their DEI programs in place and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cios-look-to-boost-tech-teams-diversity-11577469868?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">attract more diverse IT staff</a> , executives said.</p><p> “If we can&#39;t bring that diversity of thought into the workplace and into IT, at some level our solutions will be limited and flawed,” Juniper&#39;s Mandell said. “I&#39;ll feel like it&#39;s my job, regardless of what the law is, to do my best to create a set of diverse viewpoints.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=182D5840-8DBA-4B14-BE14-AE7E0EC95FCE&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fcio-affirmative-action-ruling-could-set-back-progress-in-tech-diversity-359adeea&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The Supreme Court has banned colleges from using race as admission criteria, essentially ending affirmative action. California did the same 25 years ago. WSJ explains how what happened then can offer a roadmap for what could happen now. / Photo Illustration: Madeline Marshall<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Write to Belle Lin at <a href="mailto:belle.lin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">belle.lin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/cio-affirmative-action-ruling-could-set-back-progress-in-tech-diversity-359adeea</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/cio-affirmative-action-ruling-could-set-back-progress-in-tech-diversity-359adeea<author><![CDATA[Belle Lin]]></author><category> Labor/Personnel</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>工作场所多元化</category><category>平权行动</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>Ethnic Minorities</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>社会问题</category><category>大学学院</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category> labor</category><category> personnel</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>workplace diversity</category><category>平权行动</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>ethnic minorities</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>社会问题</category><category>university</category><category>大学</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Can EVs and Solar Panels Save China’s Economy?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> China&#39;s bet on hard tech such as chips isn&#39;t going well. But the story could be different a few years down the line. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059510"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818204?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Chinese exports of electric vehicles have jumped this year, a win for Beijing&#39;s industrial policy.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Bloomberg News </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059510"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nathaniel-taplin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Nathaniel Taplin</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 17, 2023 5:47 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-evs-and-solar-panels-save-chinas-economy-44dd06dc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> China&#39;s economy <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">is sputtering</a> , but its electric-vehicle industry—and a few other choice sectors— <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/goodbye-volkswagen-chinas-new-ev-winners-bbd6d0e1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">are roaring</a> .这有关系吗？</p><p> One way to think about the country&#39;s economic policy making over the past three years is as a huge bet <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-tech-crackdown-could-backfire-badly-11627627273?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">against internet-platform businesses</a> and property companies—perceived by Beijing as security problems, drivers of financial risk and inequality, or all of the above—and a big bet <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-tech-crackdown-could-backfire-badly-11627627273?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">on semiconductors</a> , batteries and other “hard tech.” The result is now playing out, without the benefit of the Covid-induced electronics-export surge that helped paper over economic cracks in the early 2020s. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818190?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> It doesn&#39;t seem to be going very well. But over time, the story might play out differently.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-fading-recovery-tests-policy-makers-economic-playbook-8ce334f9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">China&#39;s economic output</a> in the second quarter was up 6.3% from a year earlier—impressive, if not for the fact that last spring Shanghai was locked down and a good chunk of the economy had ground to a halt. China will still probably <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-sets-economic-growth-target-of-around-5-for-the-year-88eaff89?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">achieve its growth target</a> of around 5% for 2023, but given how fast the outlook darkened last quarter—growth of just 0.8% from the quarter before—the prospects beyond that are cloudy. Most worrying is the continued <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-china-economy-capital-investment-3439d31a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">weakness in private investment</a> and consumption. The former was actually down from a year earlier in the first half, something that—apart from Covid-blasted 2020—hadn&#39;t happened since at least 2010.</p><p> But that weakness obscures some pockets of strength, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rise-of-chinas-ev-makers-puts-end-to-wests-local-dominance-775d0811?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">including electric vehicles</a> , clean power and batteries, which are all industrial policy favorites. In the first half, fixed-asset investment in electrical machinery and equipment was up 39% from a year earlier; in autos, it was up 20%. And overall private-sector manufacturing investment was up 8.6% in the first five months, slower than last year but still easily outpacing overall factory investment. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818191?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> For now, these new industries are small compared with recent leaders such as phones, computers and e-commerce. The computer and electronics industry, for example, employed around twice as many people as the auto industry did in May, according to data provider CEIC. The internet-platform economy accounts for about a quarter of urban jobs, according to Andy Rothman of Matthews Asia. Computer and phone exports came to more than $24 billion in May, far exceeding the combined $14 billion for lithium-ion batteries, electric vehicles and solar cells.</p><p> But given how quickly those latter industries are growing, that could start to change a few years down the line—if China can keep its lead. The export numbers for EVs in particular are astonishing and, along with market share gains in Russia, appear to be pulling up big parts of China&#39;s auto supply chain with them. June exports of motor vehicles and vehicle parts were up a full 40% from a year earlier. Exports of lithium-ion batteries were up 42% in May. Overall exports in June were down 12%, in large part because of weak computer and phone shipments.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> One possible scenario is a period of subpar growth and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-lost-generation-94424ee3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">high youth unemployment</a> as the economy slowly heals from the wounds to the property, software and general services sectors and as the labor force reorients itself toward new job engines like autos and batteries, followed by stronger growth in the mid-to-late 2020s as these new sectors grow to scale.</p><p> The extent of structural damage in the meantime will be significantly influenced by the aggressiveness of Beijing&#39;s fiscal and monetary support. So far, the signals aren&#39;t particularly encouraging. But it would still be unwise to write off China over the medium term—even with all its structural, demographic and political headwinds—as long as it keeps dominating a few of the key industries that will shape the global economy in the years to come. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=711BDFCA-DC73-4576-9F7D-9FC41D44AAB2&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fcan-evs-and-solar-panels-save-chinas-economy-44dd06dc&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> At this year&#39;s auto show in Shanghai, auto makers are in a race to compete with Chinese EV manufacturers. WSJ&#39;s Yoko Kubota takes a look at what&#39;s driving the latest trends. Photo: Kyodonews/Zuma Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Write to Nathaniel Taplin at <a href="mailto:nathaniel.taplin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">nathaniel.taplin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 09:47:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-evs-and-solar-panels-save-chinas-economy-44dd06dc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-evs-and-solar-panels-save-chinas-economy-44dd06dc<author><![CDATA[Nathaniel Taplin]]></author><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>Heard on the Street</category><category> DJ Exclusive Analysis - All</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>heard on the street</category><category> dj exclusive analysis - all</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Europeans Are Becoming Poorer. ‘Yes, We’re All Worse Off.’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> An aging population that values its free time set the stage for economic stagnation. Then came Covid-19 and Russia&#39;s war in Ukraine. <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817790/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="巴黎的一家餐厅。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> A restaurant in Paris. Cyril Marcilhacy/Bloomberg News <span>Cyril Marcilhacy/Bloomberg News</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001056065"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001056065"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/tom-fairless" itemprop="url" rel="author">Tom Fairless</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 17, 2023 12:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europeans-poorer-inflation-economy-255eb629"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Europeans are facing a new economic reality, one they haven&#39;t experienced in decades. They are becoming poorer.</p><p> Life on a continent long envied by outsiders for its <em>art de vivre</em> is rapidly losing its shine as Europeans see their purchasing power melt away.</p><p> The French are eating less foie gras and drinking less red wine. Spaniards are stinting on olive oil. Finns are being urged to use saunas on windy days when energy is less expensive. Across Germany, meat and milk consumption has fallen to the lowest level in three decades and the once-booming market for organic food has tanked. Italy&#39;s economic development minister, Adolfo Urso, convened a crisis meeting in May over prices for pasta, the country&#39;s favorite staple, after they jumped by more than double the national inflation rate.</p><p> With consumption spending in free fall, Europe tipped into recession at the start of the year, reinforcing a sense of relative economic, political and military decline that kicked in at the start of the century. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="960" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818002?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Europe&#39;s current predicament has been long in the making. An aging population with a preference for free time and job security over earnings ushered in years of lackluster economic and productivity growth. Then came the one-two punch of the Covid-19 pandemic and Russia&#39;s protracted war in Ukraine. By upending global supply chains and sending the prices of energy and food rocketing, the crises aggravated ailments that had been festering for decades.</p><p> Governments&#39; responses only compounded the problem. To preserve jobs, they steered their subsidies primarily to employers, leaving consumers without a cash cushion when the price shock came. Americans, by contrast, benefited from inexpensive energy and government aid directed primarily at citizens to keep them spending.</p><p> In the past, the continent&#39;s formidable export industry might have come to the rescue. But a sluggish recovery in China, a critical market for Europe, is undermining that growth pillar. High energy costs and rampant inflation at a level not seen since the 1970s are dulling manufacturers&#39; price advantage in international markets and smashing the continent&#39;s once-harmonious labor relations. As global trade cools, Europe&#39;s heavy reliance on exports—which account for about 50% of eurozone GDP versus 10% for the US—is becoming a weakness.</p><p> Private consumption has declined by about 1% in the 20-nation eurozone since the end of 2019 after adjusting for inflation, according to the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, a Paris-based club of mainly wealthy countries. In the US, where households enjoy a strong labor market and rising incomes, it has increased by nearly 9%. The European Union now accounts for about 18% of all global consumption spending, compared with 28% for America. Fifteen years ago, the EU and the US each represented about a quarter of that total.</p><p> Adjusted for inflation and purchasing power, wages have declined by about 3% since 2019 in Germany, by 3.5% in Italy and Spain and by 6% in Greece. Real wages in the US have increased by about 6% over the same period, according to OECD data. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817793?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A elderly woman leaves a food-distribution center at a Berlin church.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Markus Schreiber/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The pain reaches far into the middle classes. In Brussels, one of Europe&#39;s richest cities, teachers and nurses stood in line on a recent evening to collect half-price groceries from the back of a truck. The vendor, Happy Hours Market, collects food close to its expiration date from supermarkets and advertises it through an app. Customers can order in the early afternoon and collect their cut-price groceries in the evening.</p><p> “Some customers tell me, because of you I can eat meat two or three times per week,” said Pierre van Hede, who was handing out crates of groceries.</p><p> Karim Bouazza, a 33-year-old nurse who was stocking up on half-price meat and fish for his wife and two children, complained that inflation means “you almost need to work a second job to pay for everything.”</p><p> Similar services have sprung up across the region, marketing themselves as a way to reduce food waste as well as save money. TooGoodToGo, a company founded in Denmark in 2015 that sells leftover food from retailers and restaurants, has 76 million registered users across Europe, roughly three times the number at the end of 2020. In Germany, Sirplus, a startup created in 2017, offers “rescued” food, including products past their sell-by date, on its online store. So does Motatos, created in Sweden in 2014 and now present in Finland, Germany, Denmark and the UK</p><p> Spending on high-end groceries has collapsed. Germans consumed 52 kilograms of meat per person in 2022, about 8% less than the previous year and the lowest level since calculations began in 1989. While some of that reflects societal concerns about healthy eating and animal welfare, experts say the trend has been accelerated by meat prices which increased by up to 30% in recent months. Germans are also swapping meats such as beef and veal for less-expensive ones such as poultry, according to the Federal Information Center for Agriculture.</p><p> Thomas Wolff, an organic-food supplier near Frankfurt, said his sales fell by up to 30% last year as inflation surged. Wolff said he had hired 33 people earlier in the pandemic to handle strong demand for pricey ecological foodstuffs, but he has since let them all go.</p><p> Ronja Ebeling, a 26-year-old consultant and author based in Hamburg, said she saves about one-quarter of her income, partly because she worries about having enough money for retirement. She spends little on clothes or makeup and shares a car with her partner&#39;s father. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817996?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Weak spending and poor demographic prospects are making Europe less attractive for businesses ranging from consumer-goods giant <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PG" class="company-name">Procter &amp; Gamble</a> to luxury empire <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LVMUY" class="">LVMH</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> which are making an ever-larger share of their sales in North America.</p><p> “The US consumer is more resilient than in Europe,” <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UL" class="">Unilever</a> <span class="company-name-type">&#39;s</span></p> chief financial officer, Graeme Pitkethly, said in April.<p></p><p> The eurozone economy grew about 6% over the past 15 years, measured in dollars, compared with 82% for the US, according to International Monetary Fund data. That has left the average EU country poorer per head than every US state except Idaho and Mississippi, according to a report this month by the European Centre for International Political Economy, a Brussels-based independent think tank. If the current trend continues, by 2035 the gap between economic output per capita in the US and EU will be as large as that between Japan and Ecuador today, the report said.</p><p> On the Mediterranean island of Mallorca, businesses are lobbying for more flights to the US to increase the number of free-spending American tourists, said Maria Frontera, president of the Mallorca Chamber of Commerce&#39;s tourism commission. Americans spend about €260 ($292) per day on average on hotels compared with less than €180 ($202) for Europeans.</p><p> “This year we have seen a big change in the behavior of Europeans because of the economic situation we are dealing with,” said Frontera, who recently traveled to Miami to learn how to better cater to American customers. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="789" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817781?width=1260&amp;height=789" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> People enjoy the warm temperatures in a beach bar in the seaside resort of S&#39;Arenal on Mallorca.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Clara Margais/DPA/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Weak growth and rising interest rates are straining Europe&#39;s generous welfare states, which provide popular healthcare services and pensions. European governments find the old recipes for fixing the problem are either becoming unaffordable or have stopped working. Three-quarters of a trillion euros in subsidies, tax breaks and other forms of relief have gone to consumers and businesses to offset higher energy costs—something economists say is now itself fueling inflation, defeating the subsidies&#39; purpose.</p><p> Public-spending cuts after the global financial crisis starved Europe&#39;s state-funded healthcare systems, especially the UK&#39;s National Health Service.</p><p> Vivek Trivedi, a 31-year-old anesthesiologist living in Manchester, England, earns about £51,000 ($67,000) per year for a 48-hour workweek. Inflation, which has been about 10% or higher in the UK for nearly a year, is devouring his monthly budget, he says. Trivedi said he shops for groceries in discount retailers and spends less on meals out. Some colleagues turned off their heating entirely over recent months, worried they wouldn&#39;t be able to afford sharply higher costs, he said.</p><p> Noa Cohen, a 28-year old public-affairs specialist in London, says she could quadruple her salary in the same job by leveraging her US passport to move across the Atlantic. Cohen recently got a 10% pay raise after switching jobs, but the increase was completely swallowed by inflation. She says friends are freezing their eggs because they can&#39;t afford children anytime soon, in the hope that they have enough money in future.</p><p> “It feels like a perma-freeze in living standards,” she said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818000?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Huw Pill, the Bank of England&#39;s chief economist, warned UK citizens in April that they need to accept that they are poorer and stop pushing for higher wages. “Yes, we&#39;re all worse off,” he said, saying that seeking to offset rising prices with higher wages would only fuel more inflation.</p><p> With European governments needing to increase defense spending and given rising borrowing costs, economists expect taxes to increase, adding pressure on consumers. Taxes in Europe are already high relative to those in other wealthy countries, equivalent to around 40-45% of GDP compared with 27% in the US American workers take home almost three-quarters of their paychecks, including income taxes and Social Security taxes, while French and German workers keep just half.</p><p> The pauperization of Europe has bolstered the ranks of labor unions, which are picking up tens of thousands of members across the continent, reversing a decadeslong decline. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817780?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Bank of England has been raising interest rates to combat inflation.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jason Alden/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Higher unionization may not translate into fuller pockets for members. That&#39;s because many are pushing workers&#39; preference for more free time over higher pay, even in a world of spiraling skills shortages.</p><p> IG Metall, Germany&#39;s biggest trade union, is calling for a four-day work week at current salary levels rather than a pay raise for the country&#39;s metalworkers ahead of collective bargaining negotiations this November. Officials say the shorter week would improve workers&#39; health and quality of life while at the same time making the industry more attractive to younger workers.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What is your outlook for the economic health of Europe?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Almost half of employees in Germany&#39;s health industry choose to work around 30 hours per week rather than full time, reflecting tough working conditions, said Frank Werneke, chairman of the country&#39;s United Services Trade Union, which has added about 110,000 new members in recent months, the biggest increase in 22 years.</p><p> Kristian Kallio, a games developer in northern Finland, recently decided to reduce his working week by one-fifth to 30 hours in exchange for a 10% pay cut. He now makes about €2,500 per month. “Who wouldn&#39;t want to work shorter hours?” Kallio said. About one-third of his colleagues took the same deal, although leaders work full-time, said Kallio&#39;s boss, Jaakko Kylmäoja.</p><p> Kallio now works from 10 am to 4.30 pm He uses his extra free time for hobbies, to make good food and take long bike rides. “I don&#39;t see a reality where I would go back to normal working hours,” he said.</p><p> Igor Chaykovskiy, a 34-year-old IT worker in Paris, joined a trade union earlier this year to press for better pay and conditions. He recently received a 3.5% pay increase, about half the level of inflation. He thinks the union will give workers greater leverage to press managers. Still, it isn&#39;t just about pay. “Maybe they say you don&#39;t have an increase in salary, you have free sports lessons or music lessons,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="837" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817792?width=1260&amp;height=837" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Mathias Senn, right, a butcher in Germany&#39;s wealthy Black Forest region, couldn&#39;t find local applicants to replace four workers who are preparing to retire, so he hired an apprentice from India, Rajakumar Bheemappa Lamani.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Dominic Nahr for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> At the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/STLA" class="company-name">Stellantis</a> auto factory in Melfi, southern Italy, employees have worked shorter hours for years recently due to the difficulty of procuring raw materials and high energy costs, said Marco Lomio, a trade unionist with the Italian Union of Metalworkers. Hours worked have recently been reduced by around 30% and wages decreased proportionally.</p><p> “Between high inflation and rising energy costs for workers,” said Lomio, “it is difficult to bear all family expenses.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/europeans-poorer-inflation-economy-255eb629</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/europeans-poorer-inflation-economy-255eb629<author><![CDATA[Tom Fairless]]></author><category>领导者</category><category>wsjworld</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>Respiratory Tract Diseases</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>Outbreaks/Epidemics</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Novel Coronaviruses</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>respiratory tract diseases</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>outbreaks</category><category> epidemics</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>novel coronaviruses</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Call of Duty Will Stay on PlayStation After Microsoft-Activision Deal]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>由于监管机构担心这会损害竞争，索尼反对这项价值 750 亿美元的合并<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001058590"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="387" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818026?width=860&amp;height=387" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">微软希望确保《使命召唤》在比以往更多的平台上可用。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Avalon/ZUMA Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001058590"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sarah-e-needleman" itemprop="url" rel="author">莎拉·E·尼德曼</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nora-eckert" itemprop="url" rel="author">诺拉·埃克特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 16 日下午 1:28（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/call-of-duty-will-stay-on-playstation-after-microsoft-activision-deal-34b8ebb1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SONY" class="company-name">索尼集团</a>达成协议，如果完成对<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ATVI" class="">动视暴雪</a>750 亿美元<span class="company-name-type">的</span>收购交易，微软将在索尼 PlayStation 系统上保留动视暴雪<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-microsofts-75-billion-bid-for-activision-blizzard-hinges-on-call-of-duty-e86df589?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">广受欢迎的《使命召唤</a>》系列游戏。</p><p>索尼一直是这项大型合并的反对者，该合并的截止日期为周二。在过去一年半的时间里， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsoft-signs-call-of-duty-pact-with-nintendo-as-activision-deal-faces-scrutiny-77f47443?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">微软与任天堂、英伟达和其他竞争对手（但不是索尼）达成协议</a>，让他们在 10 年内平等地体验《使命召唤》。微软表示，索尼拒绝签署此类协议，这使其成为一个例外。现在，这家软件巨头表示，索尼也加入了。</p><p>审查该交易的监管机构的一个主要担忧是，该收购是否会损害全球视频游戏行业的竞争，即微软是否将动视暴雪的游戏（包括有史以来最受欢迎的系列游戏《使命召唤》）制作为 Xbox 独占游戏系统。一些监管机构还担心微软可能会推迟发行或降低竞争对手发行商《使命召唤》游戏的质量。微软一再表示不会做这些事情。</p><p>微软副董事长兼总裁布拉德·史密斯（Brad Smith） <a href="https://twitter.com/BradSmi/status/1680579462369353730" target="_blank" class="icon none">周日上午在推文中</a>就索尼交易表示，微软将继续专注于确保《使命召唤》在比以往更多的平台上可用。 “从此次收购的第一天起，我们就一直致力于解决监管机构、平台和游戏开发商以及消费者的担忧，”史密斯在回应微软游戏主管菲尔·斯宾塞宣布的交易时写道。</p><p>索尼确认已达成一项为期 10 年的协议。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=81754EB5-BC43-42BD-909C-41E7CB3DE1A4&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fcall-of-duty-will-stay-on-playstation-after-microsoft-activision-deal-34b8ebb1&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">由于法官裁定微软可以完成以 750 亿美元收购动视暴雪的交易，目前美国对两家公司的合并不存在任何障碍。照片：Richard B. Levine/Zuma Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>微软于 2022 年 1 月宣布<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsoft-to-buy-activision-blizzard-games-11642512435?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">计划收购动视暴雪</a>，在对视频游戏发行商的净现金进行调整后，这笔交易的估值为 690 亿美元。这些公司在欧洲、中国和其他市场获得了监管部门的批准，但在美国和英国遇到了障碍</p><p>上诉法院周五<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ftc-loses-latest-bid-to-halt-microsoft-activision-merger-19fe19ed?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">驳回了联邦贸易委员会阻止收购的最后努力</a>。在一份简短的命令中，第九巡回上诉法院驳回了 FTC 提出的阻止微软和动视暴雪合并的法院命令的请求，同时该机构对初审法院法官 7 月 11 日的裁决提出上诉。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>周五的命令有助于为微软和动视暴雪完成合并扫清道路，并向联邦贸易委员会施加压力，要求其放弃对 7 月 11 日裁决的上诉。尽管该交易在英国仍面临反对，但微软和动视上周获得了提振，英国竞争与市场管理局表示将考虑重组交易提案，这将引发新的合并调查。监管机构没有透露此类调查需要多长时间。</p><p>与此同时，微软和动视暴雪可能同意延长周二的交易截止日期。分析师表示，动视暴雪也有可能寻求重新谈判以获得更高的价格。</p><p>如果微软能够突破最后的障碍并完成交易，此次收购将推动其视频游戏业务的发展，并标志着微软战胜对大型科技交易审查更加严格的机构的努力取得了胜利。</p><p>写信给 Sarah E. Needleman <a href="mailto:Sarah.Needleman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(Sarah.Needleman@wsj.com)</a>和 Nora Eckert ( <a href="mailto:nora.eckert@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">nora.eckert@wsj.com)</a></p><p id="correction" class="correction"><strong>更正和放大</strong><br>动视暴雪是《使命召唤》视频游戏系列的制作商。本文早期版本的标题错误地称索尼是该游戏的制造商。 （7月16日更正）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 17:28:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/call-of-duty-will-stay-on-playstation-after-microsoft-activision-deal-34b8ebb1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/call-of-duty-will-stay-on-playstation-after-microsoft-activision-deal-34b8ebb1<author><![CDATA[Sarah E. NeedlemanNora Eckert]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>软件</category><category>应用软件</category><category>个人电子产品</category><category>玩具/游戏</category><category>消费品</category><category>计算</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>游戏软件</category><category>休闲/旅游用品</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>所有权变更</category><category>收购/合并/持股</category><category>反竞争问题</category><category>收购/合并</category><category>企业行动</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>兼并</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>索尼集团</category><category>6758.TO</category><category>索尼</category><category>动视暴雪</category><category>动车组</category><category>微软</category><category>微软公司</category><category>布拉德·史密斯</category><category>菲尔·斯宾塞</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策<